# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fltk-toolkit
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Within computing, **cross-platform software** (also called **multi-platform software**, **platform-agnostic software**, or **platform-independent software**) is computer software that is designed to work in several computing platforms.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] For example, a cross-platform application may run on Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform software may run on many platforms, or as few as two.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Some frameworks for cross-platform development are Codename One, ArkUI-X, Kivy, Qt, GTK, Flutter, NativeScript, Xamarin, Apache Cordova, Ionic, and React Native.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] A hardware platform can refer to an instruction set architecture.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] For example: ARM or the x86 architecture.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] These machines can run different operating systems.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Smartphones and tablets generally run ARM architecture, these often run Android or iOS and other mobile operating systems.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] A software platform can be either an operating system (OS) or programming environment, though more commonly it is a combination of both.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] An exception is Java, which uses an OS-independent virtual machine (VM) to execute Java bytecode.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] The Java language is typically compiled to run on a VM that is part of the Java platform.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] The Java virtual machine (Java VM, JVM) is a CPU implemented in software, which runs all Java code.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] This enables the same code to run on all systems that implement a JVM.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Java software can be executed by a hardware-based Java processor.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] This is used mostly in embedded systems.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Java code running in the JVM has access to OS-related services, like disk input/output (I/O) and network access, if the appropriate privileges are granted.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] The JVM makes the system calls on behalf of the Java application.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] This lets users to decide the appropriate protection level, depending on an access-control list (ACL).
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] For example, disk and network access is usually enabled for desktop applications, but not for browser-based applets.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] The Java Native Interface (JNI) can also be used to access OS-specific functions, with a loss of portability.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Currently, Java Standard Edition software can run on Microsoft Windows, macOS, several Unix-like OSs, and several real-time operating systems for embedded devices.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] For mobile applications, browser plugins are used for Windows and Mac based devices, and Android has built-in support for Java.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] There are also subsets of Java, such as Java Card or Java Platform, Micro Edition, designed for resource-constrained devices.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] For software to be considered cross-platform, it must function on more than one computer architecture or OS.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Developing such software can be a time-consuming task because different OSs have different application programming interfaces (API).
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Software written for one OS may not automatically work on all architectures that OS supports.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Just because software is written in a popular programming language such as C or C++, it does not mean it will run on all OSs that support that language—or even on different versions of the same OS.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Web applications are typically described as cross-platform because, ideally, they are accessible from any web browser: the browser is the platform.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Web applications generally employ a client–server model, but vary widely in complexity and functionality.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] It can be hard to reconcile the desire for features with the need for compatibility.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Basic web applications perform all or most processing from a stateless server, and pass the result to the client web browser.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] All user interaction with the application consists of simple exchanges of data requests and server responses.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] This type of application was the norm in the early phases of World Wide Web application development.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Such applications follow a simple transaction model, identical to that of serving static web pages.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Today, they are still relatively common, especially where cross-platform compatibility and simplicity are deemed more critical than advanced functionality.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Prominent examples of advanced web applications include the Web interface to Gmail and Google Maps.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Such applications routinely depend on additional features found only in the more recent versions of popular web browsers.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] These features include Ajax, JavaScript, Dynamic HTML, SVG, and other components of rich web applications.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Because of the competing interests of compatibility and functionality, numerous design strategies have emerged.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Many software systems use a layered architecture where platform-dependent code is restricted to the upper- and lowermost layers.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Graceful degradation attempts to provide the same or similar functionality to all users and platforms, while diminishing that functionality to a least common denominator for more limited client browsers.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] For example, a user attempting to use a limited-feature browser to access Gmail may notice that Gmail switches to basic mode, with reduced functionality but still of use.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Some software is maintained in distinct codebases for different (hardware and OS) platforms, with equivalent functionality.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] This requires more effort to maintain the code, but can be worthwhile where the amount of platform-specific code is high.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] This strategy relies on having one codebase that may be compiled to multiple platform-specific formats.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] One technique is conditional compilation.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] With this technique, code that is common to all platforms is not repeated.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Blocks of code that are only relevant to certain platforms are made conditional, so that they are only interpreted or compiled when needed.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Another technique is separation of functionality, which disables functionality not supported by browsers or OSs, while still delivering a complete application to the user.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] (See also: Separation of concerns.) This technique is used in web development where interpreted code (as in scripting languages) can query the platform it is running on to execute different blocks conditionally.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Third-party libraries attempt to simplify cross-platform capability by hiding the complexities of client differentiation behind a single, unified API, at the expense of vendor lock-in.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Responsive web design (RWD) is a Web design approach aimed at crafting the visual layout of sites to provide an optimal viewing experience—easy reading and navigation with a minimum of resizing, panning, and scrolling—across a wide range of devices, from mobile phones to desktop computer monitors.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Little or no platform-specific code is used with this technique.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform applications need much more integration testing.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Some web browsers prohibit installation of different versions on the same machine.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] There are several approaches used to target multiple platforms, but all of them result in software that requires substantial manual effort for testing and maintenance.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Techniques such as full virtualization are sometimes used as a workaround for this problem.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Tools such as the Page Object Model allow cross-platform tests to be scripted so that one test case covers multiple versions of an app.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] If different versions have similar user interfaces, all can be tested with one test case.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Web applications are becoming increasingly popular but many computer users still use traditional application software which does not rely on a client/web-server architecture.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] The distinction between traditional and web applications is not always clear.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Features, installation methods and architectures for web and traditional applications overlap and blur the distinction.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Nevertheless, this simplifying distinction is a common and useful generalization.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Traditional application software has been distributed as binary files, especially executable files.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Executables only support the platform they were built for—which means that a single cross-platform executable could be very bloated with code that never executes on a particular platform.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Instead, generally there is a selection of executables, each built for one platform.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] For software that is distributed as a binary executable, such as that written in C or C++, there must be a software build for each platform, using a toolset that translates—transcompiles—a single codebase into multiple binary executables.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] For example, Firefox, an open-source web browser, is available on Windows, macOS (both PowerPC and x86 through what Apple Inc. calls a Universal binary), Linux, and BSD on multiple computer architectures.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] The four platforms (in this case, Windows, macOS, Linux, and BSD) are separate executable distributions, although they come largely from the same source code.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] In rare cases, executable code built for several platforms is combined into a single executable file called a fat binary.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] The use of different toolsets may not be enough to build a working executables for different platforms.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] In this case, programmers must *port* the source code to the new platform.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] For example, an application such as Firefox, which already runs on Windows on the x86 family, can be modified and re-built to run on Linux on the x86 (and potentially other architectures) as well.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] The multiple versions of the code may be stored as separate codebases, or merged into one codebase.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] An alternative to porting is *cross-platform virtualization*, where applications compiled for one platform can run on another without modification of the source code or binaries.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] As an example, Apple's Rosetta, which is built into Intel-based Macintosh computers, runs applications compiled for the previous generation of Macs that used PowerPC CPUs.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Another example is IBM PowerVM Lx86, which allows Linux/x86 applications to run unmodified on the Linux/Power OS.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] A script can be considered to be cross-platform if its interpreter is available on multiple platforms and the script only uses the facilities built into the language.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] For example, a script written in Python for a Unix-like system will likely run with little or no modification on Windows, because Python also runs on Windows; indeed there are many implementations (e.g.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] The same goes for many of the open-source scripting languages.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Unlike binary executable files, the same script can be used on all computers that have software to interpret the script.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] This is because the script is generally stored in plain text in a text file.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] There may be some trivial issues, such as the representation of a new line character.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform or multi-platform is a term that can also apply to video games released on a range of video game consoles.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Examples of cross-platform games include: *Miner 2049er*, *Tomb Raider: Legend*, *FIFA series*, *NHL series* and *Minecraft*.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Each has been released across a variety of gaming platforms, such as the Wii, PlayStation 3, Xbox 360, personal computers, and mobile devices.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Some platforms are harder to write for than others, requiring more time to develop the video game to the same standard.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] To offset this, a video game may be released on a few platforms first, then later on others.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Typically, this happens when a new gaming system is released, because video game developers need to acquaint themselves with its hardware and software.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Some games may not be cross-platform because of licensing agreements between developers and video game console manufacturers that limit development to one particular console.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] As an example, Disney could create a game with the intention of release on the latest Nintendo and Sony game consoles.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Should Disney license the game with Sony first, it may be required to release the game solely on Sony's console for a short time or indefinitely.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Several developers have implemented ways to play games online while using different platforms.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Psyonix, Epic Games, Microsoft, and Valve all possess technology that allows Xbox 360 and PlayStation 3 gamers to play with PC gamers, leaving the decision of which platform to use to consumers.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] The first game to allow this level of interactivity between PC and console games (Dreamcast with specially produced keyboard and mouse) was *Quake 3*.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Games that feature cross-platform online play include *Rocket League*, *Final Fantasy XIV*, *Street Fighter V*, *Killer Instinct*, *Paragon* and *Fable Fortune,* and *Minecraft* with its Better Together update on Windows 10, VR editions, Pocket Edition and Xbox One.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Cross-platform programming is the practice of deliberately writing software to work on more than one platform.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] There are different ways to write a cross-platform application.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] One approach is to create multiple versions of the same software in different *source trees*—in other words, the Microsoft Windows version of an application might have one set of source code files and the Macintosh version another, while a FOSS *nix system might have a third.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] While this is straightforward, compared to developing for only one platform it can cost much more to pay a larger team or release products more slowly.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] It can also result in more bugs to be tracked and fixed.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Another approach is to use software that hides the differences between the platforms.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] This abstraction layer insulates the application from the platform.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Such applications are *platform agnostic*.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Applications that run on the JVM are built this way.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Some applications mix various methods of cross-platform programming to create the final application.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] An example is the Firefox web browser, which uses abstraction to build some of the lower-level components, with separate source subtrees for implementing platform-specific features (like the GUI), and the implementation of more than one scripting language to ease software portability.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Firefox implements XUL, CSS and JavaScript for extending the browser, in addition to classic Netscape-style browser plugins.
[src:fltk-toolkit/cross-platform-software] Much of the browser itself is written in XUL, CSS, and JavaScript.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] Using its own widget, drawing and event systems abstracted from the underlying system-dependent code, it allows for writing programs which look the same on all supported operating systems.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] FLTK is free and open-source software, licensed under GNU Lesser General Public License (LGPL) with an added clause permitting static linking from applications with incompatible licenses.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] In contrast to user interface libraries like GTK, Qt, and wxWidgets, FLTK uses a more lightweight design and restricts itself to GUI functionality.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] Because of this, the library is very small (the FLTK "Hello World" program is around 100 KiB), and is usually statically linked.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] It also avoids complex macros, separate code preprocessors, and use of some advanced C++ features: templates, exceptions, and run-time type information (RTTI) or, for FLTK 1.x, namespaces.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] Combined with the modest size of the package, this makes it relatively easy to learn for new users.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] These advantages come with corresponding disadvantages.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] FLTK offers fewer widgets than most GUI toolkits and, because of its use of non-native widgets, does not have native look-and-feel on any platform.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] FLTK was originally designed to be compatible with the Forms Library written for Silicon Graphics (SGI) machines (a derivative of this library called *XForms* is still used quite often).
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] In that library, all functions and structures start with `fl_`.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] This naming was extended to all new methods and widgets in the C++ library, and this prefix `FL` was taken as the name of the library.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] After FL was released as open source, it was discovered that searching "FL" on the Internet was a problem, because it is also the abbreviation for Florida.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] After much debating and searching for a new name for the toolkit, which was already in use by several people, Bill Spitzak came up with *Fast Light Tool Kit* (FLTK).
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] FLTK is an object-oriented widget toolkit written in the programming language C++.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] While GTK is mainly optimized for the X Window System, FLTK works on other platforms, including Microsoft Windows (interfaced with the Windows API), and OS X (interfaced with Quartz).
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] A Wayland back-end has been implemented and is available since release 1.4.0.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] FLTK2 has gained experimental support for optionally using the cairo graphics library.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] A library written in one programming language may be used in another language if language bindings are written.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] FLTK has a range of bindings for various languages.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] FLTK was mainly designed for, and is written in, the programming language C++.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] However, bindings exist for other languages, for example Lua, Perl, Python, Ruby, Rust and Tcl.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] FLTK includes *Fast Light User Interface Designer* (FLUID), a graphical GUI designer that generates C++ source and header files.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] This version history is an example of the sometimes tumultuous nature of open-source development.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] This is a prior stable version, now unmaintained.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] This was a development branch, long thought to be the next step in FLTK's evolution, with many new features and a cleaner programming style.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] It never achieved stability, and development has largely ceased.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] This was an attempt to take some of the best features of 2.0 and merge them back into the more popular 1.1 branch.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] All of its features have been incorporated in branch 1.3.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] This branch is in maintenance mode since release 1.4.2 (Feb.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] This branch is in early development stage.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] Since FLTK 1.5 CMake is required to build FLTK (configure/Makefile support has been dropped).
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] This branch resulted from a vision to "unfork" branches 1.x and 2.0, but it was never completed.
[src:fltk-toolkit/fltk] All efforts to develop this branch have been abandoned.
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] A **graphics library** or **graphics API** is a program library designed to aid in rendering computer graphics to a monitor.
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] This typically involves providing optimized versions of functions that handle common rendering tasks.
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] This can be done purely in software and running on the CPU, common in embedded systems, or being hardware accelerated by a GPU, more common in PCs.
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] By employing these functions, a program can assemble an image to be output to a monitor.
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] This relieves the programmer of the task of creating and optimizing these functions, and allows them to focus on building the graphics program.
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] Graphics libraries are mainly used in video games and simulations.
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] The use of graphics libraries in connection with video production systems, such as Pixar RenderMan, is not covered here.
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] Some APIs use Graphics Library (GL) in their name, notably OpenGL and WebGL.
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] Dedicated graphics processors use RAM allocated directly to the graphics processor rather than the computer’s main system memory.
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] This RAM is usually specifically selected with the expected sequential load of the graphics card in mind (see GDDR).
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] Sometimes systems with dedicated discrete graphics processors were called “DIS” systems in contrast to “UMA” systems.
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] Technologies such as 3dfx's Scan-Line Interleave, Nvidia's SLI and NVLink, and AMD's CrossFire allow multiple graphics processors to simultaneously display images on one screen, increasing the computational power available for graphics processing.
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] However, these technologies are becoming increasingly rare; most games do not utilize all the capabilities of multiple graphics processors since most users cannot afford them.
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] Today, laptops and mini-PCs require powerful integrated graphics.
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] In many cases, quality integrated graphics can replace a discrete graphics card, enhancing laptop portability and mini-PC compactness while maintaining performance.
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] Integrated graphics processors (IGPU), integrated graphics, shared graphics solutions, integrated graphics processors (IGP), or unified memory architectures (UMA) use part of the computer’s RAM rather than dedicated graphics memory.
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] IGP may be integrated into the motherboard as part of its northbridge chipset or on a single chip (integrated circuit) with the central processor (e.g., AMD APU or Intel HD Graphics).
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] On some motherboards, AMD’s IGP may use sideport dedicated memory: a separate fixed block of high-performance memory allocated for use by the graphics processor.
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] As of early 2007, computers with integrated graphics accounted for about 90% of all PC shipments.
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] They are less expensive to implement than dedicated graphics processing but generally less powerful.
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] Historically, integrated processing was considered unsuitable for 3D games or graphics-intensive applications but could run less resource-demanding programs like Adobe Flash.
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] Examples of such IGPs include offerings from SiS and VIA around 2004.
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] However, modern integrated graphics processors such as AMD Accelerated Processing Unit and Intel Graphics Technology (HD, UHD, Iris, Iris Pro, Iris Plus, and Xe-LP) can handle 2D graphics or undemanding 3D graphics.
[src:fltk-toolkit/graphics-library] In systems with a “unified memory architecture” (UMA), including modern AMD processors with integrated graphics, modern Intel processors with integrated graphics, Apple processors, PS5, and Xbox Series (among others), the CPU cores and GPU unit share the same pool of RAM and memory address space.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] (SGI) began developing OpenGL in 1991 and released it on June 30, 1992.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] It is used for a variety of applications, including computer-aided design (CAD), video games, scientific visualization, virtual reality, and flight simulation.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Since 2006, OpenGL has been managed by the non-profit technology consortium Khronos Group.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The OpenGL specification describes an abstract application programming interface (API) for drawing 2D and 3D graphics.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] It is designed to be implemented mostly or entirely using hardware acceleration such as a GPU, although it is possible for the API to be implemented entirely in software running on a CPU.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The API is defined as a set of functions which may be called by the client program, alongside a set of named integer constants (for example, the constant GL_TEXTURE_2D, which corresponds to the decimal number 3553).
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Although the function definitions are superficially similar to those of the programming language C, they are language-independent.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] As such, OpenGL has many language bindings, some of the most noteworthy being the JavaScript binding WebGL (API, based on OpenGL ES 2.0, for 3D rendering from within a web browser); the C bindings WGL, GLX and CGL; the C binding provided by iOS; and the Java and C bindings provided by Android.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] In addition to being language-independent, OpenGL is also cross-platform.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The specification says nothing on the subject of obtaining and managing an OpenGL context, leaving this as a detail of the underlying windowing system.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] For the same reason, OpenGL is purely concerned with rendering, providing no APIs related to input, audio, or windowing.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] New versions of the OpenGL specifications are released by the Khronos Group, each of which extends the API to support various new features.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The details of each version are decided by consensus between the Group's members, including graphics card manufacturers, operating system designers, and general technology companies such as Mozilla and Google.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] In addition to the features required by the core API, graphics processing unit (GPU) vendors may provide additional functionality in the form of *extensions*.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Extensions may introduce new functions and new constants, and may relax or remove restrictions on existing OpenGL functions.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Vendors can use extensions to expose custom APIs without needing support from other vendors or the Khronos Group as a whole, which greatly increases the flexibility of OpenGL.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] All extensions are collected in, and defined by, the OpenGL Registry.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The features introduced by each new version of OpenGL are typically formed from the combined features of several widely implemented extensions, especially extensions of type ARB or EXT.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] OpenGL is no longer in active development; whereas between 2001 and 2014, OpenGL specification was updated mostly on a yearly basis, with two releases (3.1 and 3.2) taking place in 2009 and three (3.3, 4.0 and 4.1) in 2010.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The latest OpenGL specification 4.6 was released in 2017 after a three-year break, and was limited to inclusion of eleven existing ARB and EXT extensions into the core profile.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Active development of OpenGL was dropped in favor of the Vulkan API, released in 2016, and codenamed glNext during initial development.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] In 2017, Khronos Group announced that OpenGL ES would not have new versions and has since concentrated on development of Vulkan and other technologies.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] As a result, certain capabilities offered by modern GPUs, e.g. ray tracing, are not supported by the OpenGL standard.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] However, support for newer features might be provided through the vendor-specific OpenGL extensions.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The OpenGL Architecture Review Board released a series of manuals along with the specification which have been updated to track changes in the API.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] OpenGL Programming for the X Window System.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Includes a poster-sized fold-out diagram showing the structure of an idealised OpenGL implementation.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] OpenGL Programming for Windows 95 and Windows NT.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] A book about interfacing OpenGL with Microsoft Windows.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] OpenGL's documentation is also accessible via its official webpage.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The earliest versions of OpenGL were released with a companion library called the OpenGL Utility Library (GLU).
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] It provided simple, useful features which were unlikely to be supported in contemporary hardware, such as tessellating, and generating mipmaps and primitive shapes.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The GLU specification was last updated in 1998 and depends on OpenGL features which are now deprecated.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Given that creating an OpenGL context is quite a complex process, and given that it varies between operating systems, automatic OpenGL context creation has become a common feature of several game-development and user-interface libraries, including SDL, Allegro, SFML, FLTK, and Qt.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] A few libraries have been designed solely to produce an OpenGL-capable window.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The first such library was OpenGL Utility Toolkit (GLUT), later superseded by freeglut.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Given the high workload involved in identifying and loading OpenGL extensions, a few libraries have been designed which load all available extensions and functions automatically.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Examples include OpenGL Easy Extension library (GLEE), OpenGL Extension Wrangler Library (GLEW) and glbinding.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Extensions are also loaded automatically by most language bindings, such as Java OpenGL, PyOpenGL and WebGL.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Mesa 3D is an open-source implementation of OpenGL.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] It can do pure software rendering, and it may also use hardware acceleration on BSD, Linux, and other platforms by taking advantage of the Direct Rendering Infrastructure.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] As of version 20.0, it implements version 4.6 of the OpenGL standard.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] In the 1980s, developing software that could function with a wide range of graphics hardware was a challenge without a cross-platform library.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Software developers wrote custom interfaces and drivers for each piece of hardware.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] This was expensive and resulted in multiplication of effort.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] By the early 1990s, Silicon Graphics (SGI) was a leader in 3D graphics for workstations.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Their IRIS GL API became the industry standard, as IRIS GL was considered easier to use, and it supported immediate mode rendering, therefore being faster than competitors like PHIGS.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] SGI's competitors (including Sun Microsystems, Hewlett-Packard and IBM) were also able to bring to market 3D hardware supported by extensions made to the PHIGS standard, which pressured SGI to open source a version of IRIS GL as a public standard called **OpenGL**.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] However, SGI had many customers for whom the change from IRIS GL to OpenGL would demand significant investment.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Moreover, IRIS GL had API functions that were irrelevant to 3D graphics.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] For example, it included a windowing, keyboard and mouse API, in part because it was developed before the X Window System and Sun's NeWS.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] IRIS GL libraries were heavily tied into SGI's proprietary graphics hardware and could not be open sourced as-is due to hardware patents and trade secrets.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] These factors required SGI to continue to support the advanced and proprietary Iris Inventor and Iris Performer programming APIs while market support for OpenGL matured.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] One of the restrictions of IRIS GL was that it only provided access to features supported by the underlying hardware.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] If the graphics hardware did not support a feature natively, then the application could not use it.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] OpenGL overcame this problem by providing software implementations of features unsupported by hardware, allowing applications to use advanced graphics on relatively low-powered systems.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] OpenGL standardized access to hardware, pushed the development responsibility of hardware interface programs (device drivers) to hardware manufacturers, and delegated windowing functions to the underlying operating system.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] With so many different kinds of graphics hardware, getting them all to speak the same language in this way had a remarkable impact by giving software developers a higher-level platform for 3D-software development.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] In 1992, SGI led the creation of the OpenGL Architecture Review Board (OpenGL ARB), the group of companies that would maintain and expand the OpenGL specification in the future.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Two years later, they also played with the idea of releasing something called "OpenGL++" which included elements such as a scene-graph API (presumably based on their Performer technology).
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The specification was circulated among a few interested parties – but never turned into a product.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Released in 1996, Microsoft's Direct3D eventually became the main competitor of OpenGL.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Over 50 game developers signed an open letter to Microsoft, released on June 12, 1997, calling on the company to actively support OpenGL.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] On December 17, 1997, Microsoft and SGI initiated the Fahrenheit project, which was a joint effort with the goal of unifying the OpenGL and Direct3D interfaces (and adding a scene-graph API too).
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] In 1998, Hewlett-Packard joined the project.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] It initially showed some promise of bringing order to the world of interactive 3D computer graphics APIs, but on account of financial constraints at SGI, strategic reasons at Microsoft, and a general lack of industry support, it was abandoned in 1999.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] In July 2006, the OpenGL Architecture Review Board voted to transfer control of the OpenGL API standard to the Khronos Group.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] OpenGL was the standard for many CAD software (such as Blender) and games in the 1990s and 2000s, and faces wide support across virtually all hardware vendors.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Despite the emergence of newer graphics APIs like its successor Vulkan or Metal, OpenGL continues to be a widely used standard.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] This continued relevance is supported by several factors: ongoing development with new extensions and driver optimizations, its cross-platform compatibility, and the availability of compatibility layers like ANGLE and Zink.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] These layers allow OpenGL to run efficiently on top of Vulkan and Metal, offering a pathway for continued use or gradual transitions for developers.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] However, the graphics API landscape has been shifting, where some companies are moving away from OpenGL.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] In June 2018, Apple deprecated OpenGL APIs on all of their platforms (iOS, macOS and tvOS), encouraging developers to use their proprietary Metal API, which was introduced in 2014.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Game developers have also begun to adopt newer APIs. id Software, who has been using OpenGL in their games since the late 1990s in games such as GLQuake or some games of the Doom franchise, transitioned away to its successor Vulkan in its id Tech 7 engine in 2016.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] They first supported Vulkan in an update for their id Tech 6 engine.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The company's first licensed use of OpenGL was in its Quake II engine, also known as id Tech 2.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] In March 2023, Valve removed OpenGL support from Dota 2 in favor of Vulkan.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Atypical Games, with support from Samsung, updated their game engine to use Vulkan, rather than OpenGL, across all non-Apple platforms.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The Khronos Group, the consortium responsible for OpenGL's development, has stopped updating OpenGL, with the last release made in 2017.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] It has not received a number of modern graphics technologies, such as hardware accelerated Ray Tracing, on-GPU video decoding, and advanced anti-aliasing algorithms like Nvidia DLSS and AMD FSR.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Another modern feature, Mesh Shaders, was initially only supported through an Nvidia exclusive extension, however in 2025, a cross-vendor OpenGL Mesh Shader extension was released.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Google's Fuchsia OS, while using Vulkan natively and requiring a Vulkan-conformant GPU, still intends to support OpenGL on top of Vulkan via the ANGLE translation layer.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The first version of OpenGL, version 1.0, was released on June 30, 1992, by Mark Segal and Kurt Akeley.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Since then, OpenGL has occasionally been extended by releasing a new version of the specification.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Such releases define a baseline set of features which all conforming graphics cards must support, and against which new extensions can more easily be written.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Each new version of OpenGL tends to incorporate several extensions which have widespread support among graphics-card vendors, although the details of those extensions may be changed.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] OpenGL 2.0 was originally conceived by 3Dlabs to address concerns that OpenGL was stagnating and lacked a strong direction.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] 3Dlabs proposed a number of major additions to the standard.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Most of these were, at the time, rejected by the ARB or otherwise never came to fruition in the form that 3Dlabs proposed.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] However, their proposal for a C-style shading language was eventually completed, resulting in the current formulation of the OpenGL Shading Language (GLSL or GLslang).
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Like the assembly-like shading languages it was replacing, it allowed replacing the fixed-function vertex and fragment pipe with shaders, though this time written in a C-like high-level language.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The design of GLSL was notable for making relatively few concessions to the limits of the hardware then available.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] This harked back to the earlier tradition of OpenGL setting an ambitious, forward-looking target for 3D accelerators rather than merely tracking the state of currently available hardware.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The final OpenGL 2.0 specification includes support for GLSL 1.10.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] OpenGL 2.1 adds support for Pixel Buffer Objects, sRGB textures and GLSL 1.20.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Before the release of OpenGL 3.0, the new revision had the codename Longs Peak.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] At the time of its original announcement, Longs Peak was presented as the first major API revision in OpenGL's lifetime.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] It consisted of an overhaul to the way that OpenGL works, calling for fundamental changes to the API.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The draft introduced a change to object management.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The GL 2.1 object model was built upon the state-based design of OpenGL.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] That is, to modify an object or to use it, one needs to bind the object to the state system, then make modifications to the state or perform function calls that use the bound object.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Because of OpenGL's use of a state system, objects must be mutable.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] That is, the basic structure of an object can change at any time, even if the rendering pipeline is asynchronously using that object.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] A texture object can be redefined from 2D to 3D.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] This requires any OpenGL implementations to add a degree of complexity to internal object management.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Under the Longs Peak API, object creation would become atomic, using templates to define the properties of an object which would be created with one function call.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The object could then be used immediately across multiple threads.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Objects would also be immutable; however, they could have their contents changed and updated.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] For example, a texture could change its image, but its size and format could not be changed.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] To support backwards compatibility, the old state based API would still be available, but no new functionality would be exposed via the old API in later versions of OpenGL.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] This would have allowed legacy code bases, such as the majority of CAD products, to continue to run while other software could be written against or ported to the new API.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Longs Peak was initially due to be finalized in September 2007 under the name OpenGL 3.0, but the Khronos Group announced on October 30 that it had run into several issues that it wished to address before releasing the specification.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] As a result, the spec was delayed, and the Khronos Group went into a media blackout until the release of the final OpenGL 3.0 spec.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The final specification proved far less revolutionary than the Longs Peak proposal.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Instead of removing all immediate mode and fixed functionality (non-shader mode), the spec included them as deprecated features.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The proposed object model was not included, and no plans have been announced to include it in any future revisions.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] As a result, the API remained largely the same with a few existing extensions being promoted to core functionality.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Among some developer groups this decision caused something of an uproar, with many developers professing that they would switch to DirectX in protest.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Most complaints revolved around the lack of communication by Khronos to the development community and multiple features being discarded that were viewed favorably by many.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Other frustrations included the requirement of DirectX 10 level hardware to use OpenGL 3.0 and the absence of geometry shaders and instanced rendering as core features.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Other sources reported that the community reaction was not quite as severe as originally presented, with many vendors showing support for the update.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] OpenGL 3.0 introduced a deprecation mechanism to simplify future revisions of the API.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Certain features, marked as deprecated, could be completely disabled by requesting a *forward-compatible context* from the windowing system.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] OpenGL 3.0 features could still be accessed alongside these deprecated features, however, by requesting a *full context*.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 8 Series and newer, ATI Radeon HD 2000 series and newer, Intel HD Graphics in Intel Sandy Bridge processors and newer.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] OpenGL 3.1 fully removed all of the features which were deprecated in version 3.0, with the exception of wide lines.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] From this version onwards, it's not possible to access new features using a *full context*, or to access deprecated features using a *forward-compatible context*.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] An exception to the former rule is made if the implementation supports the ARB_compatibility extension, but this is not guaranteed.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Hardware support: Mesa supports ARM Panfrost with Version 21.0.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] OpenGL 3.2 further built on the deprecation mechanisms introduced by OpenGL 3.0, by dividing the specification into a *core profile* and *compatibility profile*.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Compatibility contexts include the previously removed fixed-function APIs, equivalent to the ARB_compatibility extension released alongside OpenGL 3.1, while core contexts do not.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] OpenGL 3.2 also included an upgrade to GLSL version 1.50.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] OpenGL 3.3 includes minor additions, with the goal of retaining as much functionality as possible from OpenGL 4.0, while keeping support for older hardware.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Additions include new blending functions, Sampler Objects and new texture and vertex formats.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Support is also added for GLSL version 3.30, major and minor versions now match with OpenGL.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] OpenGL 4.0 was released alongside version 3.3.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] It was designed for hardware able to support Direct3D 11.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] As in OpenGL 3.0, this version of OpenGL contains a high number of fairly inconsequential extensions, designed to thoroughly expose the abilities of Direct3D 11-class hardware, such as tessellation.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Ivy Bridge processors and newer.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Haswell processors and newer (Linux Mesa: Ivy Bridge and newer).
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Additionally, this is the last core profile supported by Apple macOS.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Hardware support: Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), and Intel HD Graphics in Intel Haswell processors and newer.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Haswell processors and newer.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] (Linux Mesa: Ivy Bridge without stencil texturing, Haswell and newer), Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] VIRGL Emulation for virtual machines supports 4.3+ with Mesa 20.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Broadwell processors and newer (Linux Mesa: Haswell and newer), Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, Tegra K1.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 5000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel HD Graphics in Intel Broadwell processors and newer (Linux Mesa: Haswell and newer), Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer, Tegra K1, and Tegra X1.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Hardware support: AMD Radeon HD 7000 series and newer (FP64 shaders implemented by emulation on some TeraScale GPUs), Intel Skylake and newer, Nvidia GeForce 400 series and newer.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Apple deprecated OpenGL in iOS 12 and macOS 10.14 Mojave in favor of Metal, but it is still available as of macOS 15 Sequoia (including on Apple silicon devices).
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The latest version supported for OpenGL is 4.1 from 2011.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] A proprietary library from Molten – authors of MoltenVK – called MoltenGL, can translate OpenGL calls to Metal.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] There are several projects that attempt to implement OpenGL on top of Vulkan.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The Vulkan backend for Google's ANGLE achieved OpenGL ES 3.1 conformance in July 2020.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The Mesa3D project also includes such a driver, called *Zink*.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Microsoft's Windows 11 on Arm added support for OpenGL 3.3 via GLon12, an open source OpenGL implementation on top DirectX 12 via Mesa Gallium.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] Vulkan, formerly named the "Next Generation OpenGL Initiative" (glNext), is a ground-up redesign effort to unify OpenGL and OpenGL ES into one common API that will not be backwards compatible with existing OpenGL versions.
[src:fltk-toolkit/opengl] The initial version of Vulkan API was released on February 16, 2016.
[src:fltk-toolkit/widget-toolkit] A **widget toolkit**, **widget library**, **GUI toolkit**, **GUI framework**, **UI framework**, or **UX library** is a library or a collection of libraries containing a set of graphical control elements (called *widgets*) used to construct the graphical user interface (GUI) of programs.
[src:fltk-toolkit/widget-toolkit] Most widget toolkits additionally include their own rendering engine.
[src:fltk-toolkit/widget-toolkit] This engine can be specific to a certain operating system or windowing system or contain back-ends to interface with multiple ones and also with rendering APIs such as OpenGL, OpenVG, or EGL.
[src:fltk-toolkit/widget-toolkit] The look and feel of the graphical control elements can be hard-coded or decoupled, allowing the graphical control elements to be themed/skinned.
[src:fltk-toolkit/widget-toolkit] Some toolkits may be used from other languages by employing language bindings.
[src:fltk-toolkit/widget-toolkit] Graphical user interface builders such as e.g.
[src:fltk-toolkit/widget-toolkit] Glade Interface Designer facilitate the authoring of GUIs in a WYSIWYG manner employing a user interface markup language such as in this case GtkBuilder.
[src:fltk-toolkit/widget-toolkit] The GUI of a program is commonly constructed in a cascading manner, with graphical control elements being added directly to on top of one another.
[src:fltk-toolkit/widget-toolkit] Most widget toolkits use event-driven programming as a model for interaction.
[src:fltk-toolkit/widget-toolkit] The toolkit handles user events, for example when the user clicks on a button.
[src:fltk-toolkit/widget-toolkit] When an event is detected, it is passed on to the application where it is dealt with.
[src:fltk-toolkit/widget-toolkit] The design of those toolkits has been criticized for promoting an oversimplified model of event-action, leading programmers to create error-prone, difficult to extend and excessively complex application code.
[src:fltk-toolkit/widget-toolkit] Finite-state machines and hierarchical state machines have been proposed as high-level models to represent the interactive state changes for reactive programs.
[src:fltk-toolkit/widget-toolkit] A window is considered to be a graphical control element.
[src:fltk-toolkit/widget-toolkit] In some windowing systems, windows are added directly to the scene graph (canvas) by the window manager, and can be stacked and layered on top of each other through various means.
[src:fltk-toolkit/widget-toolkit] Each window is associated with a particular application which controls the widgets added to its canvas, which can be watched and modified by their associated applications.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] In computing, a **window** is a graphical control element.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] It consists of a visual area containing some of the graphical user interface of the program it belongs to and is framed by a window decoration.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] It usually has a rectangular shape that can overlap with the area of other windows.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] It displays the *output* of and may allow *input* to one or more processes.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Windows are primarily associated with graphical displays, where they can be manipulated with a pointer by employing some kind of pointing device.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Text-only displays can also support windowing, as a way to maintain multiple independent display areas, such as multiple buffers in Emacs.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Text windows are usually controlled by keyboard, though some also respond to the mouse.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] A graphical user interface (GUI) using windows as one of its main "metaphors" is called a windowing system, whose main components are the display server and the window manager.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] The idea was developed at the Stanford Research Institute (led by Douglas Engelbart).
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Their earliest systems supported multiple windows, but there was no obvious way to indicate boundaries between them (such as window borders, title bars, etc.).
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Research continued at Xerox Corporation's Palo Alto Research Center / PARC (led by Alan Kay).
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] During the 1980s the term "WIMP", which stands for window, icon, menu, pointer, was coined at PARC.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Apple had worked with PARC briefly at that time.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Apple developed an interface based on PARC's interface.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] It was first used on Apple's Lisa and later Macintosh computers.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Microsoft was developing Office applications for the Mac at that time.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Some speculate that this gave them access to Apple's OS before it was released and thus influenced the design of the windowing system in what would eventually be called Microsoft Windows.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Windows are two dimensional objects arranged on a plane called the desktop metaphor.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] In a modern full-featured windowing system they can be resized, moved, hidden, restored or closed.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Windows usually include other graphical objects, possibly including a menu-bar, toolbars, controls, icons and often a working area.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] In the working area, the document, image, folder contents or other main object is displayed.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Around the working area, within the bounding window, there may be other smaller window areas, sometimes called panes or panels, showing relevant information or options.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] The working area of a single document interface holds only one main object.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] "Child windows" in multiple document interfaces, and tabs for example in many web browsers, can make several similar documents or main objects available within a single main application window.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Some windows in macOS have a feature called a drawer, which is a pane that slides out the side of the window and to show extra options.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Applications that can run either under a graphical user interface or in a text user interface may use different terminology.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] GNU Emacs uses the term "window" to refer to an area within its display while a traditional window, such as controlled by an X11 window manager, is called a "frame".
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Any window can be split into the window decoration and the window's content, although some systems purposely eschew window decoration as a form of minimalism.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] The **window decoration** is a part of a window in most windowing systems.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Window decoration typically consists of a **title bar**, usually along the top of each window and a minimal border around the other three sides.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] On Microsoft Windows this is called "non-client area".
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] The border exists primarily to allow the user to resize the window, but also to create a visual separation between the window's contents and the rest of the desktop environment.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Window decorations are considered important for the design of the look and feel of an operating system and some systems allow for customization of the colors, styles and animation effects used.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] The **title bar** is a graphical control element and part of the window decoration provided by some window managers.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] As a convention, it is located at the top of the window as a horizontal bar.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] The title bar is typically used to display the name of the application or the name of the open document, and may provide title bar buttons for minimizing, maximizing, closing or rolling up of application windows.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] These functions are typically placed in the top-right of the screen to allow fast and inaccurate inputs through barrier pointing.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Typically title bars can be used to provide window motion enabling the window to be moved around the screen by grabbing the title bar and dragging it.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Some window managers provide title bars which are purely for decorative purposes and offer no window motion facility.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] These window managers do not allow windows to be moved around the screen by using a drag action on the title bar.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Default title-bar text often incorporates the name of the application and/or of its developer.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] The name of the host running the application also appears frequently.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Various methods (menu-selections, escape sequences, setup parameters, command-line options – depending on the computing environment) may exist to give the end-user some control of title-bar text.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Document-oriented applications like a text editor may display the filename or path of the document being edited.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Most web browsers will render the contents of the HTML element `title` in their title bar, sometimes pre- or postfixed by the application name.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Google Chrome and some versions of Mozilla Firefox place their tabs in the title bar.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] This makes it unnecessary to use the main window for the tabs, but usually results in the title becoming truncated.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] An asterisk at its beginning may be used to signify unsaved changes.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] The title bar often contains widgets for system commands relating to the window, such as a *maximize*, *minimize*, *rollup* and *close* buttons; and may include other content such as an application icon, a clock, etc.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Some window managers provide title bar buttons which provide the facility to minimize, maximize, roll-up or close application windows.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Some window managers may display the title bar buttons in the task bar or task panel, rather than in the title bars.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Note that a context menu may be available from some title bar buttons or by right-clicking.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Some window managers display a small icon in the title bar that may vary according to the application on which it appears.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] The title bar icon may behave like a menu button, or may provide a context menu facility. macOS applications commonly have a proxy icon next to the window title that functions the same as the document's icon in the file manager.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Some window managers display an icon or symbol to indicate that the contents of the window have not been saved or confirmed in some way: macOS displays a dot in the center of its close button; RISC OS appends an asterisk to the title.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Some tiling window managers provide title bars which are purely for informative purposes and offer no controls or menus.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] These window managers do not allow windows to be moved around the screen by using a drag action on the title bar and may also serve the purpose of a status line from stacking window managers.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Many X window managers for Unix-like systems allow customization of the type and placement of buttons shown in the title bar.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Buttons are on the left side of the title bar.
[src:fltk-toolkit/window-computing] Icon is a proxy for the document's filesystem representation.
